# Parent-Scoped CSS Variables

When building or refactoring UI components in `packages/apps/src/**/*.{ts,tsx,css}`:

- Keep primitives context-agnostic; avoid semantic context classes like `*-toolbar`, `*-list`, `*-fab` on primitive instances.
- Let parent containers own visual context by setting CSS custom properties in parent CSS files.
- Primitives consume variables with defaults, e.g. `var(--button-subtle-color, <fallback>)`.
- Keep state behavior (hover, active, disabled) in primitive CSS; let parents override via variables only.
- Prefer CSS files for styling contracts; do not centralize style presets in TypeScript objects.
- When parent width drives behavior, prefer container queries in shared CSS with media fallback.
- For SVG marks, logos, and similar accents: co-locate a `*.css` next to the component, expose tokens such as `--*-fill` (and optional `--*-height` / offset), and use a short fallback chain (for example app tokens then `currentColor`) instead of presentation props like `fill={...}` on the React surface.

Example direction:

- Parent CSS: set `--button-subtle-*` and `--button-ghost-*` on container selectors.
- Primitive CSS: read those vars in `.button--variant-*` rules with sensible fallbacks.
